After the order of free international
Cambridge—many analysts believe that the free international order has ended with the rise of China and the election of US President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he try to revive it?
Perhaps the result is not the case, but he must find some alternative choices.
Critics point out that the American order after 1945 is correct in that it is neither a global attribute nor always very free.
It would exclude more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and include many authoritarian states.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Despite this, the strongest nations must lead in creating global public goods, or else they cannot be provided – and Americans would suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a very good example.
The real goal of the Biden government should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different members participating in different matters.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 2000s, both countries were unable to balance the power of America, and America dominated, zealously pursuing the free values.
America bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without getting approval from the UN Security Council.
It also supported a "Protect Responsibility" resolution passed by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at providing protection to the citizens who were cruelly treated by their own government — and after that America used this principle in 2011 to find the reason for bombing Libya to protect the civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as American arrogance in the post-Cold War era — like when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while the defenders of this action describe it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
No matter what, the growth of China and Russia's power has more strictly limited the actions of liberal interventionism.
So, what's left?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereignty principle stipulated in the UN Charter, which stipulates that countries can only launch wars in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the cases of using force to occupy neighboring territories have been extremely rare, and once they occur, they will bear a heavy price for sanctions (such as Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council has frequently authorized the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in distress, and political cooperation has also successfully limited the expansion of mass destruction weapons and ballistic missiles.
This rule-based order dimension is still crucial.
Specifically in economic relationships, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's mixed national capitalism had supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
As a result, it would lead to a decoupling of the global supply chain, especially when national security is at stake.
Although China complains that the US is blocking Huawei and similar companies from building 5G communication networks in the West, this US position is consistent with sovereignty demands.
After all, China has blocked Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating in China for security reasons.
Talks on new trade rules would help prevent further decoupling.
Meanwhile, although the current crisis has broken out, cooperation in key financial fields is still very strong.
On the other hand, mutual dependence in the ecological field has become an insurmountable obstacle in the face of sovereignty, as the threat is transnational.
No matter how economic globalization is battered, environmental globalization will continue, for it is subject to biological and physical laws, and contemporary geopolitics has no effect on it.
All the problems mentioned above threaten everyone, but no country has the ability to solve them independently.
In problems like the 2019 new coronary pneumonia and climate change, power also has a so-called positive and dimensional aspect.
Under such a premise, it is not enough to simply think about exercising power over others.
We must also think about it from the dimension of exercising power together with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization have helped us and others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological divisions, this has not affected cooperation between China and the US.
Biden faces the challenge of whether the US and China can cooperate on creating global public goods while engaging in a traditional great power rivalry.
The digital space is a new and important issue — because it has a transnational nature, but it is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has been partially divided.
Rules on internet freedom and privacy can be made within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, if authoritarian governments also want to achieve interconnection, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the basic structure of the internet are also in their interest.
However, when they use proxy agents to launch information warfare or intervene in elections (which infringe on sovereignty), they must strengthen regulations through rules such as those negotiated by the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War to restrict escalation of maritime events (although ideological hostility still exists).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare which rules they intend to uphold and establish necessary deterrence.
Embracing the free values of the network space does not mean the United States unilaterally disarming itself.
Rather, the United States should differentiate between publicly tolerable soft power and persuasion, and secret information warfare, which should be countered when the other side launches it.
It can allow Russia and China to openly broadcast programs and broadcasts, but secret unified actions such as manipulating social media are not allowed.
And the US will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
A public opinion survey shows that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from the alliance or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values values.
If Biden is elected, the problem he faces is not whether to restore the free international order.
Problematically, can the US cooperate with core allies to promote democracy and human rights, and simultaneously cooperate with a broader range of countries to manage cross-border threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic turmoil through a rule-based international system?
